  "summary": "Hercule Poirot reveals that the cyanide used in the attempted murder was not in a bag, but was instead carried by the killer. After Tony Chapple retrieves a box of cyanide from Stephen Carter's chest pocket, Barton Russell accuses Carter of poisoning Eileen to avoid a scandal. However, Poirot intervenes to expose Russell as the true culprit. \n\nPoirot explains that during the darkness, Russell left his seat to act as a server, pouring champagne for the guests. While doing so, he placed cyanide in Polly's glass and planted the remaining cyanide box in Carter's pocket to frame him. Poirot identifies Russell's motive as financial; as Polly's guardian, Russell faced the need to account for her property once she turned twenty-one. Polly, wishing to avoid a scandal, decides not to sue Russell but insists he leave the country. Russell departs angrily, insulting Poirot.\n\nPolly explains to Poirot that she had suspected Russell's scheme after noticing he ordered yellow irises and an extra place setting for the dinner. She admits she had called Poirot using a forged, mysterious message to attract his attention because she felt an inexplicable sense of dread. Following the resolution, Carter leaves the gathering, and the remaining guests, including Poirot and Lola Walds, as well as Tony Chapple and Vera, move to the dance floor.",
